  "why": "BET enforces semantic consistency (where applicable) and maintains naturalness by design. For single-model testing (ST) BET's oracle assumes semantic equivalence (it treats a mutated input as an error only if the model prediction diverges from the original ground-truth label). BET constrains every pixel to at most ±ε from the original value (uses an L∞ bound, set to 13/255) and explicitly restricts per-byte perturbations to the two choices {+ε, −ε} relative to the original input. Its mutator logic always references the original input Eo when flipping pixel values (pixels only toggle between Eo, Eo+ε, and Eo-ε), preventing cumulative drift across iterations. The efficiency policy also keeps only a single current-best test case (P1) and derives one modified test case per iteration (P2), further avoiding uncontrolled accumulation of distortions. These controls preserve semantic similarity to the original seed and keep perturbations small and realistic, satisfying both semantic consistency (for ST) and naturalness requirements.",
